# Plan: Extract Service Layer from Express Route Handlers

## Context
The route handlers in `src/routes/products.ts` and `src/routes/orders.ts` mix HTTP concerns (parsing request params, sending responses) with business logic (filtering, validation, calculations, state mutation). This makes the code hard to unit-test and maintain. The goal is to extract all business logic into a dedicated service layer, leaving route handlers responsible only for HTTP plumbing.

---

## Architecture Decision: Error Signaling via Discriminated Unions

Service functions will return `ServiceResult<T>`:
```typescript
type ServiceResult<T> = { success: true; data: T } | { success: false; error: ServiceError }
```
- Route handlers check `result.success` and call `res.status(result.error.status).json(...)` on failure — no try/catch boilerplate needed
- TypeScript enforces exhaustive handling at compile time
- `ServiceError.status` is typed as `400 | 404` (not `number`) to prevent accidental wrong codes

Functions that can never fail (list endpoints) return their result type directly without the wrapper.

---

## Files to Modify

